msg.data:
OML4R Data Transformation: Normalization and Scaling

In this notebook, we demonstrate how to normalize and scale data using OML4R.

Using the customer insurance lifetime value data set, which contains customer financial information, lifetime value, and whether or not the customer bought insurance, we show how to normalize data using using z-score (mean and standard deviation), min-max scaling, and log scaling.

IMPORTANT: The "OML Run-me-first" notebook is available under the menu Templates -> Examples and is a pre-requisite to the current notebook.

Note : when building or applying a model using in-database Oracle Machine Learning algorithms, automatic data preparation will normalize data automatically as needed by specific algorithms. For instance, see Data Preparation for GLM .

paragraphs.title: Normalization by z-score - using mean and standard deviation
paragraphs.text:
%r

income_mean <- summarise(CUST_DF, income_mean = mean(INCOME, na.rm=TRUE))
income_std <- summarise(CUST_DF, income_std = sd(INCOME, na.rm=TRUE))

CUST_DF <- mutate(CUST_DF, INCOME_NORMALIZED = (INCOME - income_mean) / income_std)

z.show(head(round(CUST_DF[, c("INCOME", "INCOME_NORMALIZED")], digits = 4), 5))

paragraphs.title: Normalize INCOME using min-max scaling
paragraphs.text:
%r

income_min <- summarise(CUST_DF, income_min = min(INCOME, na.rm=TRUE))
income_max <- summarise(CUST_DF, income_max = max(INCOME, na.rm=TRUE))
  
CUST_DF <- mutate(CUST_DF, INCOME_MINMAX_SCALED = (INCOME - income_min) / (income_max - income_min))

z.show(head(round(CUST_DF[, c("INCOME", "INCOME_MINMAX_SCALED")], digits = 4), 5))

paragraphs.title: Filter 0 values from column TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS, then transform using base 10 logarithm
paragraphs.text:
%r

CUST_DF_FILTERED <- filter(CUST_DF, TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS > 0)

CUST_DF_FILTERED <- mutate(CUST_DF_FILTERED, LOG_TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS = log10(TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS))

z.show(head(round(CUST_DF_FILTERED[, c("TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS", "LOG_TOTAL_AUTOM_PAYMENTS")], digits = 4), 5))
